= Mathematical notation

Capital letters are used for random variables, whereas lowercase letters are used for the values of random variables and for scalar functions.

== Decision models

/ $n$: Number of alternatives.

/ $e_i (t)$: Evidence for alternative $i in [1,n]$ at time $t$.

/ $X_i (t)$: Stochastic accumulator state for alternative $i$ at time $t$.

/ $x_i (t)$: Accumulated evidence for alternative $i$ at time $t$, realization of $X_i (t)$.

/ $v_i$: Drift rate (speed of evidence accumulation) for alternative $i$.

/ $a_i$: Accumulation boundary (decision threshold) for alternative $i$.

/ $z_i$: Starting point of evidence accumulation (bias) for alternative $i$.

/ $sigma_i$: Noise magnitude of evidence accumulation for alternative $i$.
